observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the designated Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO) and the Chairperson of the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to immediately submit the following documents otherwise the transactions shall be suspended in audit:
 a. Procurement and Bidding Documents (Legal, Technical and Financial Documents of bidders);
 b. Copy of the approved contract;
 c. Appropriate approved documents containing the terms and conditions, whether operated or bare rental for heavy equipment; whether per trip or package deal; and other relevant condition;
 d. The designated dumpsite/location of dumpsite;
 e. Estimated volume in cubic meters of garbage to be hauled from area of operation, including the basis for such estimates; and
 f. Record of Attendance/Service
 Henceforth, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that payments of tipping fee for the disposal of Solid Waste Materials must be supported with complete documentation required under Sections 9.0 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 2023-004.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
 a. Submit a written explanation as to why the procurement of gasoline for privately owned motor vehicles or plate numbers not registered under the Municipality totaling P2,034,244.67 should not be disallowed in audit;
 b. Instruct his Executive Assistant to immediately submit the Monthly Report of Official Travels and the Monthly Report on Fuel Consumption for CY 2023; otherwise, the total disbursements for gasoline amounting to P6,163,856.70 shall be suspended in audit;
 c. Adopt/Install a sound system of internal control on the procedure in the issuance, control and monitoring of gasoline expense; and
 d. Henceforth, stop the practice of issuing gasoline to privately owned motor vehicles and ensure that only government-owned motor vehicles are issued gasoline for official business.
 Furthermore, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that claims for gasoline expenses must be supported with complete documentation required under COA Circular No. 77-61.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
 a. the Municipal Treasurer to update their List of Assessed Real Property Tax to show the balance of collectible taxes per property owner for the current year;
 b. the Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant with a duly certified list showing the name of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year; c. the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to coordinate in recording the amount of Real Property Tax and Special Education Tax Receivables accruing from prior years; and d. the Municipal Accountant to draw a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) at the beginning of the year by debiting Real Property Tax Receivable/Special Education Tax Receivable and crediting Deferred Real Property Tax Income/Deferred Special Education Tax Income based on the duly certified list provided from the Municipal Treasurer for fair presentation of the accounts in the Statement of Financial Position.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. direct the GAD Focal Point Designate to monitor the strict implementation of plans, programs and activities included in the GPB and fully utilize the GAD Budget to achieve its goal of promoting gender-responsive governance, protecting and fulfilling women’s human rights and promoting women’s empowerment; 
b. require the GAD Focal Point Designate to submit GAD Accomplishment Report with sufficient documentation; 
c. direct the Municipal Accountant and the GAD Focal Point Designate to coordinate and identify which particular expenses pertain to the reported PPAs and present this in the GAD Accomplishment Report; and 
d. designate or appoint another person to handle the duties and responsibilities of the GAD Focal Person.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Municipal Mayor instruct both the Municipal Accountant and Municipal General Services Officer to strictly comply with the provision of the MNGAS, Volume I, to wit:

Complete the conduct of the physical count of all properties of the Municipality. Likewise, coordinate with the Accounting Unit in order to secure relevant documents that will clarify, substantiate, and establish information leading to the completeness of the inventory reports as well as reconcile the difference in both records; 


Use the prescribed format of the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and complete the information required in the report (such as date acquired and if serviceable or not) to be submitted to the concerned Office of the Auditor on or before January 31 of each reporting period;

Continue to prepare and maintain Property Cards (PC) and Property Ledger  (PLC) for each PPE;




Exclude small items in the RPCPPE pursuant to COA Circular No. 2005-002 dated April 17, 2005; and


Segregate serviceable from the unserviceable, obsolete, fully depreciated and no longer in use PPEs and observe proper disposal by listing the same on the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), assigning appraised value to the unserviceable property by the designated Appraisal Committee and submitting the IIRUP to COA for inspection and independent valuation prior to the actual disposal of the listed PPE.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Municipal Mayor:

require the Municipal Treasurer, Accountant and the Budget Officer to explain the occurrence of cash deficit in spite of previous year’s recommendation;

require the Budget Officer to issue allotment based on the actual inflows of revenue;



require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to refrain from certifying funds availability and making payments for claims/obligations whenever there is insufficiency of funds;

prioritize expenditures only for projects, programs and activities, which are highly necessary and cannot be dispensed with;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare Cash Flow Analysis;

instruct the Local Finance Committee and all concerned officials to closely monitor the cash inflows against outflows using the Cash Flow Analysis to ensure proper utilization of the funds;




continue to strengthen the implementation of cost-cutting measures and revenue-enhancing strategies to improve the cash position of the Municipality; and

adhere strictly to the provisions of PD No. 1445, Sec 122 of GAAM, Volume I and Sections 308 and 337 of RA No. 7160.

observations.managementAction:
The Budget Officer explained that she was not furnished / provided with the Report of Cash Flows regularly, and that she never prepared / issued Allotment Release Order (ARO) whenever there is insufficiency of funds




Expenditures were prioritized as to its necessity;


Statement of Cash Flow as of year-end was prepared.


Revenue enhancing strategies and massive tax campaign were effected jointly by concerned Department/
Offices; and cost-cutting measures were undertaken following the issuances of Executive Order in various Offices /Departments;

observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the Municipal Mayors:

issue and institute standard written policies and guidelines for the hiring of JO services to categorically establish the rights and obligations of the Municipality and JO personnel and minimize the risk of applying various policies and guidelines in the hiring of JOs;

require the Municipal HRMO to initiate the preparation of the Statement of Duties and Responsibilities / Job Description of each JOs;


set also the qualification standards for the JOs and the same should be comparable with those permanent position wherein their compensation was based;

observe strictly the implementation of the hiring process for JO personnel ensuring that all JO personnel go through the said process and meet the qualifications required for each position;

document the hiring process and ensure their availability when requested for submission to the Office of the  Auditor;


consider to integrate in the JO files other documents consisting of other personal, school or employment records, but not limited to the following: (1) Birth and  Marriage Certificates; (2) Evidence of educational attainment such as elementary or high school records, diploma and/or transcript of records and training certificates; (3) NBI Clearance (especially from those who render security and janitorial services) and; (4) Medical clearance for JOs working in hospitals, clinics or other related fields to ensure that the right people are hired for the implementation of the programs of the Municipality;

complete the information indicated in the Job Order/Contract such as the duties and responsibilities, working days, etc.; and


submit to the Office of the Auditor all relevant documents needed/requested for audit to avoid the issuance of suspensions and/or disallowances.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Municipal Mayor:

initiate the filing of the appropriate criminal proceedings against the defaulting accountable officers by transmitting the complete records of the case to the Ombudsman. Administrative action may also be simultaneously instituted against the same officers for dishonesty and/or other appropriate administrative offenses, in accordance with Civil Service Law. Likewise, require the immediate refund of the unliquidated Cash Advances granted to the former Councilor and; 

Exhaust all possible steps to enforce the settlement of accountabilities from the estate of the deceased former Municipal Treasurer.
